{
  "answer": "In the opening couplet (*matla*) of this famous ghazal, Ghalib describes having a thousand desires (*khwahishein*) so intense that **each one is powerful enough to kill him**—to make his spirit (*dam*) cease entirely.[^1] Yet paradoxically, despite so many of his aspirations (*armaan*) being fulfilled, he remains unsatisfied, as if they were still \"too few\" (*kam nikle*).\n\nThe full couplet in translation reads:  \n\"A thousand wishes, each could make my spirit cease;  \nSo many of my dreams came true, yet brought so little peace.\"[^1]\n\nThis sets the philosophical tone for the ghazal, contrasting boundless human longing with the futility of fulfillment.[^2]\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/70-hazaaron-khwahishein-aisi-ke-har-khwahish-pe-dam-n/translation/#p-fcc8ca).\n\n[^2]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [chapter](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/70-hazaaron-khwahishein-aisi-ke-har-khwahish-pe-dam-n/translation/).",
